# Frontend Design

- Design screens for clarity first: strong hierarchy, obvious primary actions, and enough spacing to scan quickly.
- Prefer Material UI primitives and the shared theme before custom CSS or one-off utility stacks.
- Reuse theme tokens for color, spacing, typography, radius, and shadows instead of hardcoding visual values.
- Keep layouts simple and responsive: start with one clear desktop structure and ensure it collapses cleanly on smaller screens.
- Every interactive view should handle loading, empty, success, and error states intentionally.
- Default to accessible patterns: semantic structure, visible labels, keyboard support, focus visibility, and sufficient contrast.
- Keep forms short, with helpful validation and clear submit outcomes near the action area.
- Use accent color sparingly to highlight the most important action or status, not every element on the page.
- Favor consistent card, list, and page-section patterns over inventing a new layout for each screen.
- Use interesting components from component libraries such as shadcn and reactbits

```tsx
// Prefer theme-driven UI.
<Card sx={{ p: 3, bgcolor: "background.paper" }}>
  <Stack spacing={2}>
    <Typography variant="h5">Queue status</Typography>
    <Button variant="contained">Add source</Button>
  </Stack>
</Card>
```
